\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Horizontal bars give the mean oracle-referenced EIE recovery error for each of the four panel-formation strategies, ordered best (lowest, top) to worst (highest, bottom); the whiskers are 95\% confidence intervals over 96 seeds and the value beside each bar is the mean +/- half-interval, all from source \breaktt {output/data/sweep\_aggregated.csv} (profile manuscript\_contrast, hash fda4da941cf0). Read it as the ceiling each upstream choice imposes on the downstream blind estimator: competence-first selection sits far left (near-zero error) while the other three strategies cluster together to its right. Claim: the upstream formation rule, not the estimator, sets the no-answer-key error ceiling, and the competence-first-vs-rest gap dwarfs anything the estimator does on a fixed panel; caveat: only the competence-first separation is resolved --- representative, random, and single-bloc selection are statistically indistinguishable from one another, as the power/separation layer certifies.}}{14}{figure.caption.3}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:ranking}{{2}{14}{Horizontal bars give the mean oracle-referenced EIE recovery error for each of the four panel-formation strategies, ordered best (lowest, top) to worst (highest, bottom); the whiskers are 95\% confidence intervals over 96 seeds and the value beside each bar is the mean +/- half-interval, all from source \protect \breaktt {output/data/sweep\_aggregated.csv} (profile manuscript\_contrast, hash fda4da941cf0). Read it as the ceiling each upstream choice imposes on the downstream blind estimator: competence-first selection sits far left (near-zero error) while the other three strategies cluster together to its right. Claim: the upstream formation rule, not the estimator, sets the no-answer-key error ceiling, and the competence-first-vs-rest gap dwarfs anything the estimator does on a fixed panel; caveat: only the competence-first separation is resolved --- representative, random, and single-bloc selection are statistically indistinguishable from one another, as the power/separation layer certifies}{figure.caption.3}{}}
